<HEADLINE> Shoot-at-Sight Orders in India's Hyderabad City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Shoot-at-sight orders have been
issued after two days of violence and arson, in which four people
were killed in the old city of Hyderabad, capital of Andhra
Pradesh in southeastern India, official sources said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Two people were killed in police firing while two others
including a woman were stabbed to death in the city which
witnessed large-scale rampage. As a mob went on the rampage
torching shops and stabbing passers-by, police opened fire,
killing two persons. Around 32 persons were injured in a stabbing
and arson spree in communally sensitive areas of the city, Andhra
Pradesh Chief Minister N. C. Naidu told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Naidu said the violence was the handiwork of anti-social
elements.
</P>
<P>
The violence erupted Friday when groups of youth, enraged over
mysterious pamphlets that denigrated a particular community, went
berserk burning buses, stabbing people and attacking shops and
vehicles, leading to police firing at two places. Apart from local
police, additional central forces were called in to tackle the
situation, the same sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
