<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA: U.S. Air Traffic Errors up 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Air traffic controller errors in
the United States have increased 20 percent this year, with the
most troublesome trends involving communications and memory
lapses, Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting FAA officials, the Washington Post said Saturday that in
airport control towers across the nation, where controllers handle
numerous complicated aircraft movements, these lapses often
involved visual misjudgments.
</P>
<P>
On April 3, an Air Canada Airbus A-319 narrowly escaped a
collision with a U.S. Airways DC-9 at the La Guardia airport in New
York because of visual misjudgment. The two aircraft came as close
as six meters.
</P>
<P>
The FAA documents, according to the Post, showed the error
rates were the highest in the New York region, with tower
operations making 1.69 errors per 100,000 operations at La Guardia
Airport and 1.38 errors at John F. Kennedy Airport. The New York
regional control center, which handles flights entering the New
York airspace, also had the highest error rate, 1.98, compared
with a national average of 0.55.
</P>
<P>
The three Washington airports were in the middle range of error
rate, with 0.58 at the Reagan National Airport, 0.52 at the
Baltimore-Washington Airport and 0.41 at the Dulles Airport. The
Washington regional control center ranked fifth among 21 centers,
with an error rate of 1.29, according to the FAA.
</P>
<P>
The number of errors in the first seven months of fiscal 1998,
starting October 1, rose to 1,282 from 1,068 in 1997, according to
a FAA document.
</P>
<P>
While operational errors increased 21 percent, the portion of
errors involving planes on the ground increased 49 percent.
"Operational deviations," in which a controller violates a rule
but creates no potential safety problem, have increased
dramatically, up about 80 percent over the past year through the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Facing the sharp increase in controller mistakes, the FAA
ordered the retraining of 10,000 of the nation's 18,000
controllers recently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
