<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maputo Development Corridor Construction Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the 400
million U.S. dollars Maputo Development Corridor toll road was
officially launched in the border town of Ressano Garcia,
Mozambiuqe Saturday, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela and his Mozambican
counterpart Joaquim Chissano and thousands of people in the town
participated in the grand ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The corridor has been dubbed the largest infrastructure
project on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
After unveiling a commemorative plaque, both Mandela and
Chissano stressed the importance of the corridor to uplift local
communities.
</P>
<P>
It was the first fruit of a broader alliance between South
Africa and Mozambique, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
"As we cooperated in our struggle for liberation, as we stood
together against oppression and violence, so we now take hands to
improve the lives of our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Local communities had to seize the opportunities created by
the corridor, Mandela said, stressing, "we need participation,
not only between our two countries, but also between our
provinces, cities and sectors."
</P>
<P>
Chissano said the project was proof of the capacity of
Mozambique and South Africa and of Africa's potential to attract
investment.
</P>
<P>
"We are saying to the world that Africa is not only a zone of
instability, but rather one of economic progress and
development," Chissano said.
</P>
<P>
Chissano assured Mozambicans the toll road would "draw us out
of poverty, because it will bring about job creation", noting,
"we go to South Africa seeking jobs but now the jobs are coming
to us."
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people gathered to witness the launch of the
construction. A military band singers and dancers entertained the
guests.
</P>
<P>
Communities from Mpumalanga Province, South Africa bordering
with Mozambique were bussed to the event and hundreds of VIP
guests, many wearing traditional outfits and dress arrived by
train.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the toll road between Witbank, South Africa
and Maputo, the capital of Mozambique was expected to be
completed in three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
