<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- Ethiopia said that 44 people were killed and 135
wounded in the bombing of northern Ethiopian town of Mekelle on
Friday by the Eritrean warplanes.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued by Tigray State Council in Mekelle, capital
city of the state, said, "The victims of the raid on Friday were
students in school compounds and families who happened to be in
the vicinity looking for their children were also bombed in the
second raid by Eritrean warplanes."  (Ethiopia-Eritrea-Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif left here
Saturday for a visit to the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and Saudi
Arabia to discuss the situation arising from India and Pakistan's
nuclear tests last month.
</P>
<P>
Talking briefly to reporters before departure, Sharif said he
had sought advice from leaders of the two brotherly Gulf countries
 after New Delhi set off five nuclear devices on May 11 and 13.
(Pakistan-PM-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee said
Saturday that his country would not succumb to any pressure to
give up its nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
"We will not come under any pressure from the nuclear powers,"
Vajpayee said when inaugurating a training camp for parliament
members of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) in Haryana State near
the country's capital. (India-Nuke Program)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The death toll of Germany's worst postwar railroad
crash rose to 101 after rescuers found another three bodies at the
crash site near the northern German town of Eschede, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The InterCity Express, the country's fastest train, derailed at
11:10 Wednesday morning near Eschede rail station and slammed into
a nearby road bridge, bringing hundreds of tons of concrete to
crash down onto the middle section of the train. (Germany-Train
Crash-Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The talks between the striking pilots of Air France
and the company's management broke down early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
If the talks can resume on Monday as the earliest, time is
running out for preparing for the opening day of the Football
World Cup finals in the country on June 10, as the preparation
time for pilots to fly planes needs 48 hours. (France-Airline
Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan Saturday called for active international
engagement in defusing the exacerbated tension in South Asia by
helping Pakistan and India find an amicable solution to their
disputes.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly news briefing here late in the afternoon, a
Foreign Office spokesman said the international community should
engage itself along with Pakistan and India to find "an equitable,
just and expeditious settlement" of the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he said, "tension will not go away from South Asia
where the situation has exacerbated after the region's
nuclearization."  (Pakistan-India-Call) 
</P>
</TEXT>
