<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls on India to Join Non-Proliferation Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
deeply concerned over the nuclear tests conducted by India and
Pakistan, on Saturday urged India to sign the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Indian President Vadjpayee
Yeltsin said that the Indian-Pakistani nuclear competition has
spread far beyond the region. It undermines the nuclear
non-proliferation regime and sets a dangerous precedent of nuclear
weapons spread.
</P>
<P>
In view of that India assured of stopping nuclear tests and
determining to join the de-facto moratorium on nuclear testing and
taking part in the disarmament talks in Geneva, the Russian
president stressed the need for New Delhi to take further positive
steps in this direction.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed possible forms that Russia
directly promotes a dialogue between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three weeks India and Pakistan carried out
nuclear tests that provoked a great deal of attention over the
world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
