<HEADLINE> Iraqi President's Special Envoys Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's
special envoys Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan and Speaker of
National Assembly Saadoun Hammadi returned to Baghdad Saturday
after visits to north Africa and Southeast Asia respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan told the Iraqi News Agency (INA) that his visits to
Algeria, Tunisia and Morocco are important and fruitful as far as
the lifting of the embargo and relations with these countries are
concerned.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the week-long visits, he delivered messages
from President Saddam to Algerian President Liamine Zeroual,
Tunisian President Zine Al-Abidine Ben Ali and Moroccan King
Hassan II.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said he briefed the Arab leaders on Iraq's
relationship with the Security Council and the Special Commission,
known as UNSCOM overseeing disarmament in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He also discussed with them the issue of lifting the embargo
now that Iraq has abided by its obligations under the
U.N. resolutions, and U.S. and (UNSCOM Chairman) Richard Butler's
designs of hostility against Iraq, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said the three Arab leaders expressed their
understanding of the suffering of Iraqis as a result of the
embargo, adding that they said they would work to bring an end to
this embargo.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, the speaker returned to Baghdad from a 10-day
Southeast Asia tour which took him to India and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi told INA that he conveyed letters from President Saddam
to leaders of India and Malaysia on the effects of sanctions on
the Iraqi people and Iraq's relations with UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The speaker said that Indian and Malaysian officials had
expressed their sympathy to and solidarity with the Iraqi people
in their efforts for lifting the sanctions as soon as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
