<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Planes Bomb Eritrean Air Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian air force
announced Saturday that it has inflicted heavy damages on
Eritrean war planes and air force complex in air raids launched
on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Ethiopian Air Force was quoted by the
official Ethiopian News Agency as saying that "Ethiopian fighter
jets in attack sorties Friday and Saturday have bombed the
Eritrean Air Force base."
</P>
<P>
"The Ethiopian air force in air raids it launched in
retaliation to attacks by the Eritrean war planes on civilian
targets in Mekelle has inflicted heavy damages on the Eritrean
war planes and air force complex," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The statement denied reports on the downing of Ethiopian
fighter jet Friday and described the reports as "unfounded."
</P>
<P>
However, the statement admitted the downing of a war plane
among fighter jets that were in action in the air raids launched
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As Ethiopia and Eritrea pressed on with their ground and air
war Saturday, Eritrean gunners claimed they had shot down another
Ethiopian warplane on a bombing sortie over Asmara and captured
its pilot. In turn, Ethiopia captured an Eritrean pilot near its
northern town of Mekele after he ejected from his crippled
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The border dispute between the two Horn of Africa countries
turned violent since May when either side accused the other of
invasion.
</P>
<P>
Their dispute centered on a rocky 400 square km triangle of
border land which both countries claim.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian and Eritrean guerrillas fought side by side in the
long struggle which eventually ousted military dictator Mengistu
Haile Mariam in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea was rewarded for its efforts with independence after a
referendum in 1993, and the two countries enjoyed friendly ties
until the long-running border dispute turned violent on May 6.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have mobilized thousands of veterans of the 30-year
liberation struggle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
