<HEADLINE> EgyptAir Cancels Flights to Addis Ababa, Asmara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's national carrier EgyptAir has
called off all its flights to both Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa
and Eritrean capital Asmara as fightings erupted between the two
Horn of African nations.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency reported that Mahmoud el-Rawi,
director general of EgyptAir foreign stations, said Saturday's
scheduled flight to the region was canceled and that passengers
were notified.
</P>
<P>
Other flights have likewise been grounded pending improvement
in the situation, he added.
</P>
<P>
A Civil Aviation Authority official said an international
aviators announcement purporting the closure of air routes between
the warring neighbors is a warning to international flights not
to enter the airspace of Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several world countries have started to devise means
to evacuate their nationals from Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian warplanes bombed a combined military-civilian airport
as well as the outskirts of Asmara Saturday, escalating the battle
since May 6 for a 400 square kilometers rocky triangle of land
along their western border.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, among the world's poorest nations, are at
odds over at least six areas along their common border. Eritrea
gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
