<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy in Angola for New Sanctions on UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Blondin Beye, the United Nations
special envoy in Angola, has proposed in the U.N. Security
Council new sanctions against the opposition National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
In his speech at a meeting Friday, Beye also warned against a
likely new war in the country, saying the Angolan government
might resort to armed force toward UNITA's obstructions to the
1994 Lusaka Peace Accord, which may lead to new armed conflicts,
the Angola News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Security Council were reported to have
revealed that the sanctions on UNITA which were under study by
the Council include the suspension of UNITA-controlled diamond
trade to cut short its source of income.
</P>
<P>
The serious crisis now in the Angolan Peace Process resulted
from the fact that UNITA has refused to hand over the four
sensitive regions under its control, including Bailundo and
Andulo, two central cities in which its headquarters are located.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Monteiro, Portuguese ambassador to the U.N. and
rotating chairman of the Security Council, told reporters after
the meeting that the situation in Angola is "very serious" and
that new sanctions must be imposed on the former UNITA movement
to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the United States, Russia and Portugal,
the three observer countries of the Angolan Peace Process, have
proposed a draft resolution on new sanctions against UNITA so as
to force it to implement the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council wished very much to save the peace
process and bring to an end the prolonged civil war so that the
Angolan people could lead a peaceful life, Monteiro said.
</P>
<P>
The Council meeting also denounced UNITA for its violation of
the peace agreement by not disarming all its armed units.
</P>
<P>
If the resolution is passed, it will be the third sanctions on
UNITA since the end of 1992 when the civil war broke out after
the country's first multi-party elections. In 1993, the Council
imposed an arms and ammunition embargo on UNITA whereas in
October, 1997 it resolved once again to restrict UNITA
leadership's foreign visits and close the rebel movement's
offices in foreign countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
