<HEADLINE> Baghdad Mourns Young Victims of Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A mass funeral procession was held
Saturday in Baghdad for 41 Iraqi children who died because of
shortage of medicine and food under the eight-year-old
U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The procession, attended by members of a Jordanian medical
delegation which arrived here Friday on board a plane and families
of dead children as well, started from Al-Rashid street and headed
for the building of the U.N. Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Sultan al-Shawi, chairman of the Iraqi Society for Supporting
Children which organized the procession, said the United States
and Britain should be responsible for the deaths because they
blocked the approval of contracts sealed under the oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal, Iraq is allowed to
export limited amount of oil to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies, but funds allocated for the medical sector
are far from being enough.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shawi called on the international community and humanitarian
organizations to condemn these actions and work for the lifting of
the sanctions imposed by the U.N. after Iraqi invasion of Kuwait
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics given by the Iraqi Red
Crescent Society, the mortality rate for Iraqi children under
five is on the increase, with nearly 4,000 deaths being registered
in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
