<HEADLINE> PNA Renews Call for Urgent Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) renewed its call in Gaza Saturday for an urgent
Arab summit to study ways of saving the Middle East peace
process, according to a Jerusalem-based Palestinian press service.
</P>
<P>
The Media and Communication Center (JMCC) quoted PNA Minister
of Public Works Azzam Al-Ahmad as saying that it is very important
for Arab states to agree to a Palestinian call for such a summit.
</P>
<P>
The proposed summit should be held whatever there is progress
in the peace process or not, he said.
</P>
<P>
The renewed call came as the prospect for an immediate Arab
summit seems diminishing as there are differences among Arab
states over how to deal with Israel. Some want to see a hardline
Arab stance while some others embrace more moderate tones.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahmad said that besides the peace process, issues such as
Arab solidarity to confront the modern problems should also be
discussed in the summit.
</P>
<P>
Blaming the Israeli side for blocking the peace process, PNA
Chairman Yasser Arafat has asked for an Arab summit to help break
the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made arduous trips to most of the Arab capitals to garner
their support for this purpose. But the time and the venue for
the summit has not been fixed so far.
</P>
<P>
The United States has reportedly asked for a delay in convening
such a summit to allow it more time to convince Israel to accept
its proposal on a 13.1 percent troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu indicated earlier
this week that he would accept the U.S proposal, and Israel would
carry out a combined 15 percent pullback before the two sides
entering into the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat told a PNA cabinet meeting Friday evening in Gaza
that the PNA would not agree to the Israeli offer. He asked Israel
to accept and implement the U.S. proposal as the second stage
redeployment and carry out the third phase pullback before
permanent talks open.
</P>
<P>
"Troop redeployment is a matter of principle and there is a
U.S. proposal and the Israeli side must implement it," Arafat
reportedly told the cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
