<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000 Families to Be Resettled in Rwandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The municipal authority of Rwandan
capital Kigali has started from this month to execute a
comprehensive project of resettling about 10,000 families who are
supposed to be evicted from the houses they occupy illegally.
</P>
<P>
The project "Tente Temporary Permanent" (TTP) was conceived by
the Kigali city authority (P.V.K.) with an objective of providing
houses for the shelterless while returning the houses to their
legal owners.
</P>
<P>
It is being supported financially and materially by the
government, the U.N. Development Program (UNDP), the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and other local and foreign
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The evicted are being allocated with plots, tents, iron
sheets, nails, brick-making machine, stones and architectural
designs prepared by the P.V.K," said Kayumba Eudes, director of
Urban Planning and Development. The beneficiaries are expected to
provide labor in brick-making and construction.
</P>
<P>
Already more than 1,000 families have started to be catered
for by the scheme in such special areas of Gitega and Kimisange
surveyed and developed by the city Authority.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Kigali urban prefecture confirmed that about
3,097 people have filed cases to resume their houses.
</P>
<P>
Housing crisis in Kigali has constantly been escalating since
the end of genocide in 1994 when the city population was said to
have redoubled from 200,000 to 500,000 after massive return of
old and new case refugees.
</P>
<P>
The old case returnees and some genocide survivors were
occupying the houses of the new returnees who fled the country
during the genocide.
</P>
<P>
The P.V.K. initiated an intensive campaign last year to move
out those families occupying other's houses as it was affecting
the success of the national policy for unity and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
But the campaign ended up unpopular as it was not providing an
alternative exit, which the T.P.P project is now refurnishing.
</P>
<P>
"Technically the project is very difficult to run but
politically it should be done, since there is no way
reconciliation can be advanced while some people are still
occupying others' properties," said Kayumba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
