<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Hails Three-Country Oil Cut Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran said Saturday that it backed
the decision made by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico to further
cut their oil output to shore up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted an unnamed Oil Ministry
official as saying that Iran supported any collective action by
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) and non-OPEC producers to boost oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Oil ministers of Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and non-OPEC Mexico
Thursday reached an agreement in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to
further cut their oil production by 450,000 barrels per day (bpd)
from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Saudi Arabia will cut output by 225,000
bpd, Venezuela by 125,000 bpd and Mexico by 100,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
The three countries reached a deal in March to reduce their
production in order to trim world oil supply by 1.6 million to 2
million bpd as oil prices slumped to a nine-year low on the world
market due to sagging demand.
</P>
<P>
The move was followed by OPEC's decision to cut 1.25 million
bpd starting from April 1 till the end of this year. The world
market was little moved by the cut.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the world oil benchmark Brent crude traded at
13.08 U.S. dollars per barrel, as against 18 dollars a year
earlier, while Gulf heavy crude remained at 8.88 dollars a barrel,
lagging far behind last year's 13.65 dollars.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's President Obeid Bin Saif al-Nasir has said recently that
further production cuts were needed to raise the stagnant oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the third largest oil producer in the world, has seen a
sharp fall in oil earnings in the past Iranian calendar year
ending March 20 with only 15.8 billion dollars fetched, far below
the target of 17.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said that the issue of oil output cuts
will figure high at the upcoming OPEC ministerial meeting to be
held in Vienna on June 24.
</P>
<P>
The 13-member OPEC, established in 1960, supplies 40 percent of
world's total of 76.5 million bpd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
