<HEADLINE> Construction Started on Maputo/Witbank Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Construction on the Maputo/Witbank
road started Saturday with South African President Nelson Mandela
and his Mozambican counterpart Joaquim Chissano unveiling a
commemorative plaque.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony in Ressano Garcia, a small Mozambican town near
the border with South Africa, Chissano said the ceremony is held
two years after the implementation of Maputo Development
Corridor. It indicates not only the confidence both Mozambique
and South Africa have in exploring the region but also the
enhanced bilateral cooperation and friendship, Chissano noted.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the Maputo/Witbank road, he said, is also an
evidence that countries in the region have the good political
will in carrying out large scale projects, which will surely
speed up the economic integration of the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also appealed to the business community to invest in
the corridor and the Incomati River valley so as to absorb modern
technology and create job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also said the impact of the Maputo/Witbank road will
exceed the bilateral scope. It shows that a southern Africa
committed to progress and development, unity and cooperation is
emerging.
</P>
<P>
The 500-kilometer-long Maputo/Witbank road built with 400
million U.S. Dollars, is part of the Maputo Development Corridor,
which is dubbed the largest infrastructure project on the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
Once the road is completed, it will link the industrial
centers in South Africa to Maputo port, shortening the export
route for South African products.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 government officials, parliament members, and
people of the two countries attended the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
