<HEADLINE> Zambia's Tourism Potential Described as Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A foreign tour operator said
Saturday that Zambia's tourism potential is great and the country
could become a major tourist destination in Africa because of the
attractive liberalization policies the government pursuits.
</P>
<P>
Nick Moyo, General Manager of the United Tourism Company, said
here there is need to market the country's vast tourism
attractions abroad so that more tourists travel to it.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of tour operators is still low and there is
need for the private sector to invest in the sector to create job
opportunities and help the country develop economically.
</P>
<P>
He cited south Luangwa and lower Zambezi national parks as the
tourist attraction centers.
</P>
<P>
Moyo, however, said that high entry fees into the national
parks and visa charges prevailing in Zambia are discouraging a
number of tourists from coming into the country.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's tourism earnings reached 78 million U.S. Dollars in
1997 compared with 70 million Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's tourism industry is not satisfactory due to limited
infrastructure and unsatisfactory management of parastatal
facilities. However, several positive developments have emerged
including the establishment of eight private airlines and
privatization of many previously government-owned lodges.
</P>
<P>
Last year the government adopted a tourism development
strategy including development of private sector-based tourism.
</P>
</TEXT>
