<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Frogs Doing Fine in Chilly Liaoning Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Table frogs from the United States
have proved capable of resisting the severe cold and are doing
well in northern China's Anshan City.
</P>
<P>
When they were first brought to the city in northeast China's
Liaoning Province last June, experts doubted whether the 10 pairs
of American frogs were strong enough to withstand the cold weather.
</P>
<P>
Not only have the creatures survived, but their 4,000
offsprings also have been doing fine.
</P>
<P>
Their survival is attributable to a special method of warmth in
which their pool is wrapped up in plastic sheeting in winter. The
water is kept at 0.5 meters deep, with the ice measuring some 0.1
meter. Workers daily drill holes into the ice to ensure a supply
of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
The frog population had grown to 10,000 by May. Another 10,000
are expected to propagate by this fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
