<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slow Peace Process in Somalia Arouses Grave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) has expressed grave concern over the lack of
substantive progress toward sustaining and advancing an
all-inclusive process of peace and national reconciliation in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The 68th Ordinary Session of OAU Council of Ministers
therefore called on the international community to closely
coordinate their efforts with OAU and the Inter-Governmental
Authority for Development (IGAD) in order to facilitate a
negotiated and sustainable settlement of the conflict in that
country.
</P>
<P>
A resolution adopted by the Council of Ministers meeting which
is ending here Sunday night asked all OAU member states and the
international community at large to provide political,
diplomatic, financial and material support.
</P>
<P>
The support should be aimed "to bolster the overall process of
peace-building and national reconciliation, through assistance
provided for the rehabilitation and reconstruction of Somalia,
especially in those areas of the country where commitment to
peace and national reconciliation has been demonstrated," the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
In that regard, "the ultimate responsibility for resolving the
conflict in Somalia rests with the Somali people themselves," it
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting, however, did not forget the appeal to
the United Nations to take speedy action to set up the trust fund
in support of the peace process in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The ministers expressed dismay at the spiraling violence and
increased insecurity arising from the intensification of intra-
and inter-clan disputes.
</P>
<P>
They thus called upon the Somali faction leaders to make
determined effort to bring to an end these disputes which have
led to death and destruction of property.
</P>
<P>
They also called on the international community to provide
urgent emergency humanitarian relief to those affected by the
flooding in Somalia and assist displaced persons for
resettlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
