<HEADLINE> OAU Urges Angola's UNITA to Fully Demilitarize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) has urged the National Union for Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) to ensure full, unconditional demilitarization
of its remaining forces, especially its residual and absentee
troops.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the last phase of the 1994 Lusaka
Protocol, aimed at bringing lasting peace to the country, had
been delayed, a situation that has caused grave concern at the
68th Ordinary Session of OAU Council of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the meeting, OAU Secretary-General Salim
Ahmed Salim noted that a total of 7,877 soldiers had so far been
registered after handing over 7,275 pieces of weapons.
</P>
<P>
However, UNITA had failed to comply with the agreed timetable
and the remaining provisions of the Lusaka Protocol as well as
the relevant United Nations Security Council resolutions, he
added.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted by the session, the Council of
Ministers appealed to all the OAU member states and the
international community to scrupulously adhere to and implement
the U.N. Security Council sanctions imposed on UNITA.
</P>
<P>
"This is the only way to guarantee the irreversibility of the
peace process in Angola," the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
It also appealed to the international community to render
necessary humanitarian and economic assistance for the
reconstruction of Angola.
</P>
<P>
This is especially important for the rehabilitation of key
infrastructure destroyed during the war and the restoration of
the economic fabric of the country as well as de-mining
activities, the resolution said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
