<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> River Clean-up Leads to Wild Geese or ducks' Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Fushun, a renowned
coal capital in northeast China's Liaoning Province, have sighted
more than 1,000 wild geese or ducks swimming on the Hunhe River,
which had suffered serious pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
"Blocks of black oil have been floating on the water for
decades," recalled one old man who lives near the river. In 1971
the river unexpectedly caught fire and spread far and wide for
more than 100 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Residents along the river said they had never imagined that the
river could have become as clear as it is today.
</P>
<P>
The city of Fushun has encountered serious environmental
problems since the early 1970s. Local residents even joked that birds
flying through the region would be dyed black.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the serious pollution to the booming
petrochemical enterprises of the 1970s, which had poor equipment
for pollution control and ignored environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Since the mid-1980s, however, the city has made a great effort
to help local companies replace equipment for efficient waste
control. A loan of one billion yuan (120 million US dollars) from
the World Bank has been used to set up a sewage treatment plant,
which is expected to handle some 500,000 tons of sewage
each day when finished by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Some rare wildlife such as wild boar, roe deer and black bear,
which had disappeared in the region for many years, began to
return to the industrial city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Refuses to Return Sphinx's Beard: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain has refused to return the
missing part of Sphinx's beard to Egypt, the Egyptian Gazette
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' negotiations on the issue have recently
broken down, the newspaper report said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian side could not accept British side's terms for
returning the beard, said the report, without giving further
details.
</P>
<P>
In other similar negotiations with Egypt, the British side
requests as a must the high-tech protection of the antiquities
after they are returned, a precondition Egypt says too harsh to be
accepted.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman for the British Culture Ministry was
quoted in the report as saying that Britain has no plan to hand
back the missing part of Sphinx's beard at all.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the British Museum, which houses the beard
along with a selection of rare ancient Egyptian antiquities, is
applying a law enacted in 1863 that prohibits handing back any
rare piece of antiquity.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's remarks dashed the hope that the beard would be
returned to Egypt to help support the neck of the 4,600-year-old
lion-man.
</P>
<P>
A 10-year restoration project on the giant was just completed
last month.
</P>
<P>
The missing part of the beard, which was obtained by the
British Museum a century ago after it was discovered accidentally
in sand by Italian Giovanni Caviglia in 1816.
</P>
<P>
The beard, also known as false beard, is part of the giant's
royal headdress. The headdress bears a cobra and a false beard,
the symbol of virility of the pharaohs.
</P>
<P>
The lion-man is 20 meters tall and 57 meters long, representing
King Khafre by giving him a lion's body and a pharaoh's head. For
centuries, it faces eastwards and guards the Giza necropolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deteriorating Marine Economy Draws Attention of Senior Legislator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- While land resources are
depleting, marine development is becoming the lifeblood of the
nation and must be well-protected, according to a senior
legislator.
</P>
<P>
Qu Geping, chairman of the Environment and Resources Committee
under the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC), said in a
recent interview that along with faster development in the coastal
areas, human activities have greatly undermined the natural marine
ecology.
</P>
<P>
Qu's remarks were specifically in regard to the serious damage
to the coral reefs and mangrove woods in China's tropical province
of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
"Human activities have ultimately resulted in damage to the
marine ecological system, decreasing species of marine life and
heavier natural disasters," said Qu, who, also former director of
the State General Administration of Environmental Protection, has
been engaged in his environmental protection career for more than
three decades.
</P>
<P>
In Hainan Province, local residents spurred by immediate
economic returns have been exploiting coral reefs to make
handcrafts or lime, according to Yang Kunhan, deputy director of
the Hainan Provincial Department of Oceanography.
</P>
<P>
Serious damage to the coral reefs has led to corroded coasts,
fallen coconut trees, silted ports and shipping channels, and
reduced marine life, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the quantity of mangrove woods has declined during
the past several years, to the detriment of the balance of the
coastal ecological system, he said.
</P>
<P>
Aware that the problems are threatening local farming,
fisheries and tourism, Hainan provincial officials are working
hard to rescue the precious marine ecology and protect local
marine life through working relevant regulations and establishing
nature reserves, Yang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
