<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Envoy Hopes for Peace With Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government's top
representative in Zimbabwe Sunday said his government was still
giving peace a chance in the troubled border area with
neighboring Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Markos Geta, Charge d'Affaires at the Ethiopian Embassy in
Harare told the Zimbabwe News Agency that Ethiopians regarded
Eritreans as their blood brothers and sisters who for centuries
shared a common history and culture that should not be torn apart
by territorial disputes.
</P>
<P>
"We are still giving a chance for peace and we are expecting
the call from the United States and Rwanda for a peaceful
settlement will be successful," said Geta.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea centers around a
rocky 400-square-kilometer triangle in the Badme region claimed
by both Horn of Africa countries.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea began a series of air raids Friday,
turning a month-long border conflict into a battle of the skies.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Ethiopian Embassy in Harare had made any
approaches to Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe as current
Chairman of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to seek his
intervention, Geta said they had not done so because they
expected the situation to return to normal.
</P>
<P>
"We thought that the Eritreans would change their state of
mind before we brought the issue to the OAU. We were hoping that
things would improve, that is why we did not consult President
Mugabe," he said. 
</P>
