<HEADLINE> Tianjin Port Strengthening Infrastructure Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, the largest port city in
north China will put in 2.7 billion yuan (325 million US dollars)
in infrastructure construction this year, aiming to have a
handling capacity of 100 million tons in the first decade of the
next century.
</P>
<P>
As China's largest man-made port, Tianjin now has fortynine
10,000-ton berths, with an annual handling capacity in excess of
60 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructure construction this year will center on
building five berths and remodeling eight others. The five berths
include two coal terminals, one coke wharf, one non-metal ore
wharf and an oil wharf.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin port also expanded its main channel from 150 meters
wide to 180 meters for larger ships.
</P>
<P>
The port also plans to build two wharves for international
passenger transport and one container wharf. 
</P>
