<HEADLINE> Russia Lacks Money in Fighting Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Lack of funds has hampered the
efforts in Russia to prevent the spread of the HIV virus that
causes AIDS, the most threatening disease in the history of
mankind which is still incurable.
</P>
<P>
"To combat AIDS, money is needed, but there is none," Vadim
Pokrovsky, general director of the Russian Center for Preventing
and Combating AIDS, told the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
In May, the center had received only 6,000 rubles (about 1,000
U.S. dollars), just enough for procedures to determine the stage
of infection of five patients, the general director said.
</P>
<P>
In the past 11 years, 8,428 HIV carriers were registered in
Russia, 294 of them have died of the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the number of HIV carriers has grown considerably
as more drug addicts are infected through syringe-sharing. Last
year alone, about 4,500 HIV carriers were identified, nearly as
many as the figure registered totally in the previous decade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moscow and the Moscow region would become areas with
a high rate of HIV infection by the end of this year, the report
quoted Pokrovsky as warning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
