<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Fires Striking Pilots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) announced
Sunday that those striking pilots who defied a return to work
order on or before noon Sunday have already lost their employment
status.
</P>
<P>
"Some pilots were able to beat the deadline but those remained
defiant were, in accordance with law and jurisprudence, declared
as having lost their jobs with the airlines," PAL said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The airlines Saturday fired all 29 officers of the Airline
Pilots Association of the Philippines (ALPAP) which staged an
indefinite strike Friday evening, almost paralyzing the firm's
flight operations.
</P>
<P>
It also warned the other striking members of the 620-member
union to report for work until Sunday noon or else lose job.
</P>
<P>
PAL said it was forced to take the drastic step to protect the
interest of its over 13,000-strong work force as well as that of
the riding public.
</P>
<P>
The airlines also accused the striking pilots of holding the
riding public's livelihood and well-being hostage through their
disruption of operations.
</P>
<P>
In pursuit of returning to normal operations, PAL said it has
started processing applications for pilot positions.
</P>
<P>
But union spokesman Florendo Umali said all union members had
agreed to support the 29 union leaders.
</P>
<P>
Some 250 pilots marched in front of the PAL flight operations
center to show their defiance of the return to work order,
according to Umali.
</P>
<P>
PAL said earlier that its decision to terminate the employment
of all striking pilots was based on an article under the Labor
Code and on applicable Supreme Court decisions.
</P>
<P>
Under the Labor Code, a strike that is undertaken despite the
issuance by the secretary of labor of an assumption is illegal,
and the union officers and members are deemed to have lost their
employment status for such an act.
</P>
<P>
By launching the strike Friday, the ALPAP openly defied two
orders of the secretary of labor who already assumed jurisdiction
over the dispute and had prohibited the union from aggravating the
situation, PAL said.
</P>
<P>
The strike was triggered by the sacking of a 45-year-old pilot
who was ordered to retire last year by PAL management in
accordance with an earlier collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached between PAL and the union, PAL
management has the right to retire pilots who have already
surpassed their normal retirement dates regardless of their age.
</P>
<P>
The ALPAP said the pilot was too young to retire, and also
accused the airline of cutting pilot rest hours and harassing
union members.
</P>
<P>
PAL senior vice president for sales and services Avelino
Zapanta said the company stood to lose millions of dollars if the
strike continued, adding the company would only "manage certain
critical flights" with 25 pilots recalled from administrative
duties.
</P>
<P>
PAL was only able to operate five of the 38 scheduled
international flights and 14 of its 132 domestic flights out of
Manila Sunday. Thousands of passengers are stranded in airports in
Manila and other cities in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
