<HEADLINE> Pakistan Condemns India for Fomenting Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Information Minister
Mushahid Hussain Sunday strongly condemned India for fomenting
state terrorism via its intelligence outfit while expressing
regret for the loss of life in the train bomb blast early in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
Mushahid said in a statement Sunday evening that the government
had evidence of the involvement of India's Research and Analysis
Wing (RAW) in the current series of terroristic acts, which first
targeted a cinema in Lahore and now a train through a time-bomb.
</P>
<P>
The main suspect in Friday's cinema blast killing three and
injuring one in Lahore, capital of eastern Punjab province, has
been proved to be an Indian national.
</P>
<P>
The information minister's statement came after a bomb blast
took place in a passenger train early Sunday morning in southern
Pakistan. Twenty-three people were killed and over 30 injured in
the blast.
</P>
<P>
He said that another RAW agent, captured recently in Sialkot
district close to the Indian border, has confessed to involvement
in earlier similar acts of terrorism that resulted in 10 bomb
blasts in 9 weeks, killing 16 and injuring 93 during the first
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of these acts of terrorism being fomented by India
is two fold: to put pressure on Pakistan since the Indian BJP
government's militarism is fueled by fundamentalism; and to divert
attention away from domestic political and economic frustrations
since the Indian nuclear tests have backfired and divided India,"
He said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan strongly condemns these Indian actions and urges the
international community to take note of the designs of a regime
which is apparently rattled by the restoration of strategic
balance in South Asia, is now resorting to terrorist actions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Pakistani Foreign Office in a statement also
accused the Indian intelligence agency of masterminding the train
bomb blast, saying the blast "is obviously an abominable
RAW-sponsored terrorist act."
</P>
<P>
"Continuation of such acts of terrorism and making of innocent
civilians their victims would vitiate the atmosphere for a
constructive engagement for finding solutions to the problems in
the region," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The international community has stressed the necessity for a
dialogue to remove the root cause of the tensions in a nuclearized
South Asia," the statement said. "It is also clearly its
responsibility to denounce such acts of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The bomb, reportedly planted in the middle of a carriage, went
off at about 4:10 a.m. (local time) Sunday when the train heading
for the northwestern city of Peshawar was running about 50 km away
from Sukkur, a major city in Pakistan's southern Sindh province.
</P>
</TEXT>
