<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Atmospheric Research Begins on Qinghai-Tibet Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China formally started its second
scientific research on atmospheric circulation on Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau in tandem with the establishment of a headquarters in the
Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
China's Meteorological Bureau and the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS) led nearly 10 nationwide research and
higher-education institutions to carry out the scientific
endeavor, which includes theoretical research and on-the-spot
experiments in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Scientific workers in the region have regulated the
high-altitude surveying and ground monitoring since May 10.
</P>
<P>
The research will focus on atmospheric physics on the plateau,
the world's highest, to improve the accuracy of forecasting
natural disasters, experts said. In addition, the scientific group
will study monsoon circulation on the plateau, which greatly
affects the overall climate of the world.
</P>
<P>
The former State Science and Technology Commission approved the
research in 1995 and listed it as a key national research
project. China had organized the first research of this kind in
1979.
</P>
<P>
Local scientific workers undertook the surveying and monitoring
in experiment sites at Gerze, Lhasa, Nagqu, Nyingchi, Qamdo,
Shiquanhe and Tingri and dealt with all computerized data during
the experiments.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, scientists will perform research on the ozone layer
and radiation from the sun.
</P>
<P>
A senior official in the autonomous region pledged to support
the scientific work and coordinate with concerned departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
