<HEADLINE> Lebanon Starts Third Round of Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Residents in the capital Beirut as
well as south Lebanon began voting on candidates for municipal and
mayoral posts early Sunday in the first ever local elections in 35
years.
</P>
<P>
This is the third round since May 24, when the elections,
expected to be held on four consecutive Sundays, were
inaugurated. The police stepped up security around polling
stations and at main road intersections.
</P>
<P>
The polls opened at 07:00 local time (0400 GMT) and will close
at 17:00 local time (1400 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Voters queued up to cast their ballots in the capital as
Lebanese leaders called for more support to Christian candidates
in the elections in order the keep the delicate sectarian balance
between the Muslims and the Christians in the country.
</P>
<P>
Muslim political and spiritual leaders have urged Muslim voters
in Beirut not to ignore Christian candidates running for the 24
seats in the municipal council. There are about 177,000 eligible
Christian voters and 200,000 eligible Muslim voters in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday's elections in Tripoli, the country's second
largest city, were seen as disruptive to the Muslim-Christian
balance, which turned out in favor of the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
This time the Sunni Muslim Prime Minister Rafik Hariri asked
the Muslims to vote for Christian candidates to avert a repeat of
the Tripoli debacle and keep a peaceful coexistence between the
two sects.
</P>
<P>
The country protracted and bloody civil war from 1975 to 1990
was caused basically by the political imbalance between Muslims
and Christians.
</P>
<P>
The race for the municipal posts in south Lebanon will go on
mainly between two Shiite Muslim factions - the resistance group
of Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the Amal Movement led by House
Speaker Nabih Berri.
</P>
<P>
The two groups have long been vying for control of the Shiite
Muslims, the country's largest religious sect.
</P>
<P>
During the first round of elections, Hezbollah defeated Amal
in Beirut's southern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Voting will be held next Sunday in the eastern Bekaa Valley,
thus bringing the country's local elections to an end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
