<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early-Warning Weather Forecast System for Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Chongqing
Municipality will spend 70 million yuan (8.4 million U.S. dollars)
in the next two years to set up an early warning system for
torrential rains for the safety of the Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
After construction is completed for another 30 automatic
meteorological stations, the accuracy of the forecast for
torrential rains and other kinds of natural adversities is
expected to rise by 5-to-10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Du Shunyi, director of the Chongqing Municipal Meteorological
Bureau, the early warning system will include comprehensive
meteorological detecting devices, information networks,
information analysis and forecast, and meteorological services.
</P>
<P>
Sophisticated radar is capable of monitoring all the project
areas and an early warning system can provide timely and accurate
weather forecast services for the project, Du said.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing gigantic Three Gorges Project is the world's
largest water control project, which, with a total investment of
around 200 billion yuan (24.1 billion U.S. dollars) is expected to
be completed by the year 2009.
</P>
<P>
As part of the project area, Chongqing is located in an area
frequently hit by torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Du said, the system will also use satellite remote
sensing technology and a ground monitoring system to provide data
on environmental and ecological pollution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
