<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Longest Bridge to Be Completed Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Jamuna Multipurpose Bridge, the
longest bridge in Bangladesh, will be completed on schedule before
its inauguration on June 23, Communication Minister Anwar Hossain
Manju said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Everything was going on smoothly to ensure the completion of
the 4.8-kilometer bridge as scheduled in Tangail district, some 70
kilometers northwest of Dhaka, and preparations were being made
for the inauguration ceremony, the communication minister told
reporters of the Overseas Correspondents Association of
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, also named "Bangabhandu Bridge" after Bangabhandu
Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, the first prime minister of independent
Bangladesh, would be inaugurated by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
on June 23, the date on which the ruling Awami League assumed
power in 1996.
</P>
<P>
At a cost of 900 million U.S. dollars, the construction of the
bridge started in October 1994. Upon its completion, it would
become the longest bridge in South Asia, and the 11th longest in
the world, Abdullah, deputy principal manager of the Jamuna
Multipurpose Bridge Project, told reporters on a separate
occasion.
</P>
<P>
Besides road transportation, the bridge with rails could also
be used for train service, for power and gas transport, and for
telecommunications, he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, the Asian Development Bank and Japan each
provided 200 million U.S. dollars for the construction of the
bridge, with the rest of the fund from the Bangladeshi government.
</P>
<P>
Deltaic Bangladesh in South Asia is crisscrossed by many
rivers, with the Jamuna River, which flows through the country,
dividing it into two distinct and separate regions.
</P>
<P>
At present, passengers and freight traffic between the
northwestern and eastern regions of the country are transported
across the Jamuna River by ferry, which has been an impediment to
the development of an integrated transportation and energy network
in the country, and to its overall economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
