<HEADLINE> Iraq to Stop Accepting Humanitarian Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has announced that it will no
longer accept humanitarian donations from other countries and
world organizations, the Iraqi News Agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"From now on, the cabinet decided, the Iraqi government will
not accept any assistance in kind subsumed under humanitarian
aid," the Iraqi cabinet said in an announcement made after a
meeting chaired by President Saddam Hussein Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Iraq needs no money given away by foreign countries and people,
and the Iraqi people are not so lazy as to ask for help from
others, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that Iraq used to be an aid donor to many states,
institutions and figures.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet, meanwhile, expressed appreciation of all parties
and people who have donated humanitarian aid to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It voiced hope that all parties that have sympathy for Iraq
would continue with their support for Iraq's call to have the
international sanctions on the country lifted.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council imposed the crippling
sanctions on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. Iraq has
blamed the sanctions for causing sufferings of its people due to
shortage of food and medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
