<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nepal Striving to Conserve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has been
taking various measures in recent years to try to stop the
environment from degrading further for the benefit of integrated
national development.
</P>
<P>
In order to minimize the environmental problems through
institutional efforts, the government established the Ministry of
Population and Environment in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
There are many areas requiring the continuation of
environment-friendly activities, but due to socio-economic
conditions of the country, the ministry is committed to
implementing the primary functions such as environment
conservation, pollution control, enforcement and monitoring of
environmental standards, and environmental assessment with its own
initiative, the ministry said Sunday in a press release.
</P>
<P>
In the past two and a half years, the ministry has launched
public awareness programs through publishing journals, newsletters
and posters.
</P>
<P>
It has supported the concerned agencies to institutionalize
vehicle emission test in the capital city of Kathmandu, use
alternative fuel, and has made policy decisions to reduce air
pollution at source by discouraging the use of old vehicles.
</P>
<P>
It has also developed a working modality to work closely with
the non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
In addition to continuing research studies to generate
information, the ministry will accomplish the preparation of
background working papers on water resources, agriculture,
forestry, urban pollution and human health, impact of fiscal
policies on the environment, and environmental institutions,
legislation and conventions for the formulation of an
environmental perspective plan, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The drafting of the implementation strategy for
environment-related conventions will be completed by the end of
this fiscal year which ends in July, it added.
</P>
<P>
Nepal participated in the first U.N. Conference on Human
Environment held on June 5-16, 1972 in Stockholm, Sweden. And
during the U.N. Conference on Environment and Development held in
June 1992 in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, it signed the Convention on
Biological Diversity and the U.N. Framework Convention on Climate
Change.
</P>
<P>
At present, Nepal is a party to 16 environment-related
conventions, and has developed action plan to implement some of
them.
</P>
<P>
On the home front, the Environment Protection Act 1996 and the
Environment Protection Rules 1997 have been enforced since June
1997. The legislation contains several provisions to
institutionalize environmental assessment system, pollution
prevention and control and heritage conservation.
</P>
<P>
It also contains provisions to punish those who degrade the
environment and empowers the government to provide additional
concession and facility to encourage the adoption of the process
and the technology which brings positive impact on the
environment.
</P>
<P>
Under the act, the Environment Protection Council under the
chairmanship of the prime minister has been established to provide
policy guidance and suggestions to the government, and to ensure
coordination among different agencies.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, an Environmental Conservation Fund has also been
established, the ministry noted.
</P>
<P>
To raise public awareness, the World Environment Day is
celebrated in Nepal each year on June 5 with specific programs.
From 1988 onward, the day has been celebrated as a national
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion this year, an Environmental Awareness Fair was
organized by government ministries and non-governmental
organizations on June 5-7 in Kathmandu to draw the attention of
the society toward the existing environmental problems and to
create awareness regarding possible solutions.
</P>
<P>
On this auspicious occasion, the Ministry of Population and
Environment published the State of the Environment for the first
time as a government document.
</P>
<P>
The report notes that major environmental issues in the
Himalayan kingdom have been emerging from land degradation,
depletion of forest resources, unscientific urban development,
discharge of untreated effluents and disposal of solid wastes.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Minister for Population and Environment Purna Bahadur
Khadka told a press conference held here Sunday that in addition
to the U.N. system and such regional inter-governmental bodies as
South Asian Cooperative Environmental Program and South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), other regional and
international organizations like Asian Development Bank, United
Nations Development Program, World Conservation Union and
International Center for Integrated Mountain Development have also
extended cooperation to Nepal in its efforts to conserve the
environment.
</P>
<P>
However, the State of the Environment warns that based on the
present trend, environmental problems like resource degradation
and pollution are likely to continue in the future, and resource
constraints and the continuation of the existing consumption
pattern will likely accelerate environmental degradation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
