<HEADLINE> EU Asks Turkish Cypriots to Join Accession Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Task Force
chief Nikolaus van der Pas has appealed to the Turkish Cypriots
for their joining the Cypriot government controlled by Greek
Cypriots in the EU accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Van der Pas, director general of the European Commission's Task
Force for accession negotiations, made the call at the end of his
three-day fact-finding mission here, which is part of Cyprus'
accession process.
</P>
<P>
"Regrettably, the Turkish Cypriots decided not to join the
negotiations," van der Pas said, adding "we hope that sooner
rather than later they will change their minds," Cyprus Mail
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Slovenia and
Estonia have started accession talks with the EU since March.
</P>
<P>
Van der Pas said Cyprus was very much determined to make
progress in the negotiations, and had the political readiness to
welcome the Turkish Cypriots in the talks.
</P>
<P>
President Glafcos Clerides has proposed that Turkish Cypriots
participate in the government's team to negotiate the island's
membership to the EU, but the idea was rejected by the Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish Cypriot community must understand that the EU
accession process is very much considered to be of benefit to both
communities on the island," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added "when the Turkish Cypriots think of the EU, they
should think of it as a positive project. It is a peaceful
project bringing people together for their own benefit."
</P>
<P>
Denktash walked out of the negotiations with Greek Cypriots
last summer to protest the EU's decision to start accession talks
with Cyprus, not his strong supporter Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is recognized only by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
