<HEADLINE> Survey: 83 Percent of Smokers Would Obey Ban in Public Places </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 percent of smokers
said that they would not light up in public places where "No
Smoking" signs had been posted, according to the results of a
survey released today.
</P>
<P>
After a survey was conducted among 1,000 smokers in downtown
areas of Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu and Xi'an, an
opinion poll organization affiliated with the State Statistics
Bureau revealed that 83 percent of smokers are unanimous in their
views that they would not violate a ban on smoking in public
places.
</P>
<P>
Some 82.58 percent of male smokers and 90.57 percent of females
said that they would comply with rules in their cities.
</P>
<P>
However, about 2 percent of smokers said that they would still
smoke despite no-smoking signs. However, no female smokers said
they would defy a smoking ban in public places, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 92 percent of smokers with college degrees such as
teachers and doctors said they would "surely obey a no-smoking
rule."
</P>
<P>
The results of the survey also suggest that local authorities
should make the "No-smoking" signs more eye-catching in public
place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
