<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Govt to Resettle Ex-soldiers With $8M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government will
allocate eight million U.S. Dollars this year to rehabilitate the
demobilized soldiers of the two warring sides, a senior military
official has said.
</P>
<P>
The money will be distributed as financial assistance in line
with the national reconstruction program, General Antonio De
Andrade who is in charge of the rehabilitation of the demobilized
soldiers said in central town Kuito Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 86,686 soldiers of the opposition National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) who have been demobilized
according to the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol will benefit from the
sum, the Angolan News Agency reported Sunday, and so will more
than 80,000 former government soldiers who have been demobilized
according to the Bicesse Peace Accord signed in Portugal in 1991.
</P>
<P>
General Andrade said that the Angolan government will greatly
encourage the development of small businesses so as to
accommodate the demobilized soldiers across the nation.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation of the demobilized soldiers has been
supported by the United Nations Development Program and the
International Labor Organization.
</P>
<P>
According to the program on the reconstruction of Angola's
infrastructure adopted at the round-table meeting in Brussels in
1995, the U.S., Denmark, Sweden, the Netherlands and other
members of the European Union will also provide assistance for
the rehabilitation of the demobilized soldiers.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Angolan government has used various
channels to resettle the demobilized soldiers. Rehabilitation of
ex-soldiers is one of the major issues to be addressed by the
government and a vital matter which hinges on the stability of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has established a number of vocational
education centers in several areas to train the demobilized
soldiers so that they will be able to have skills for making a
living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
