<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran Mayor Rejects Charges as "Baseless" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein
Karbaschi on Sunday rejected all charges brought against him at
the first session of an open trial of him, calling them "baseless."
</P>
<P>
The charges were read in the court as embezzlement of 14.53
billion rials (about 260,000 U.S. dollars) plus 90,000 dollars, 60
full-priced gold coins and 80 half-priced gold coins, receiving
bribes, mismanagement of public funds, illegitimate ownership of
public properties and fraud.
</P>
<P>
He was also charged with purchasing a building worth 3,800
million rials (about 680,000 million dollars) for an unorthodox
institute and granting 250 million rials (44,643 dollars) to two
former district mayors to fund their election campaigns for the
fifth Majlis (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi defended himself at the open trial which formally
started work Sunday morning at Tehran's special judicial complex
under strict security, with the deployment of hundreds of riot
police equipped with sticks and arms.
</P>
<P>
The trial will last for several days since the case was too
complicated and involved many officials.
</P>
<P>
On April 4, Karbaschi was detained by the conservative
judiciary on multi-charges, but was released 11 days later
following direct intervention from top leaders including President
Mohammad Khatami, former President Hashemi and the supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi was the highest ranking official charged with
embezzlement since the Islamic revolution in 1979. The case
intensified political struggle between the conservatives and
moderates, tipping political factions against each other.
</P>
<P>
The moderates claim the case was politically motivated withe
the aim to weaken the government of President Khatami, who enjoyed
strong support from Karbaschi and his followers in the
presidential elections in May last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservatives attack the moderates for abusing
the freedom and democracy proposed by Khatami, vowing to punish
those who violate the laws.
</P>
<P>
It is believed here that the trial would touch off another
round of political scuffle between the two rival factions, despite
that top Iranian leaders have repeatedly called for unity to
"preserve the Islamic principles." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
