<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Discusses Troop Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet held its weekly
meeting Sunday morning and discussed its troop redeployment in the
West Bank, but no decision was made concerning this matter.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said that during the meeting, Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu denied that Israel is about to sign an
agreement with the Palestinians on the second troop redeployment
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that Israel will not ask the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) to rectify its charter calling for the
destruction of Israel, the Office added.
</P>
<P>
Israel's contacts with the U.S. Administration are continuing
on the troop redeployment issue, particularly on the third stage
troop pullback from the West bank, but so far no decision was made
by the Israel side, Netanyahu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the last several days, local media gave significant
coverage about Israel's decision on the troop redeployment, saying
that Netanyahu has agreed to a 15 percent withdrawal, with 13
percent to be carried out during the second stage and the
remaining 2 percent in the third phase before the two sides enter
into the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
But at its weekly cabinet meeting in Gaza Friday, the PNA
declared that the U.S. proposal of a 13.1 percent redeployment
will not be accepted as an alternative to a complete Israeli
withdrawal from all Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat told the cabinet that the PNA
accepted the U.S. proposal in principle in order to push the
peace process forward, but the Palestinian side will not abandon
any of the redeployment phases because the only basis that will
allow the peace process to succeed is Israeli withdrawal from all
occupied land.
</P>
<P>
Arafat insisted that the third stage redeployment must include
the entire withdrawal from the West Bank, indicating that he will
not accept the 2 percent which would be counted as the third
pullback.
</P>
<P>
PNA also said the Palestinian National Council had already
amended its charter two years ago and rectified the provisions
calling for the destruction of Israel and there is no need to do
it again.
</P>
<P>
During Sunday's cabinet meeting, officials from the Israel's
General Security Service briefed the ministers on the military
situation in Gaza Strip and the West Bank, suggesting to reopen
the Shuhada Street in the West Bank city of Hebron, which was
closed to traffic due to conflicts between the local Palestinians
and Jewish settlers long time ago.
</P>
<P>
But National Intrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, who insists
on handing over 9 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians,
opposed the reopening of the street. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
