<HEADLINE> Israeli Teachers Strike Against Pension Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Israeli teachers
Sunday held a one-day strike to protest against the government's
plan to reform the pension system.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said that about 1 million children were affected
by the strike as the teachers of kindergartens, elementary
schools, junior and high schools walked out of their job.
</P>
<P>
The proposed pension reform would shift the currently
non-contributory pension for teachers to a cumulative pension.
</P>
<P>
Avraham Ben Shabat, secretary-general of the Teachers Union,
said that the reform would hurt the interests of teachers as well
as the educational system.
</P>
<P>
Shabat warned that the opening of the next school year could
be delayed if the government did not changed its stance.
</P>
<P>
But Education Ministry Director-General Ben Zion Dell denounced
the strike, noting that the strike was "unnecessary and
untimely."
</P>
<P>
"Even if their demand regarding the pensions is justified, the
activists are hurting the image of the teachers that the Education
Ministry has been working so hard to nurture," Dell said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
