<HEADLINE> Pakistan Blames India for Train Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Sunday accused the
Indian intelligence agency of masterminding the train bomb blast
in southern Pakistan, killing 23 and injuring more than 30.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blast in the train Khyber Mail "is obviously an
abominable terrorist act sponsored by (India's) Research and
Analysis Wing (RAW)," the Pakistani Foreign Office said Sunday
afternoon in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, reportedly planted in the middle of a carriage, went
off at about 4:10 a.m. (local time) Sunday when the train heading
for the northwestern city of Peshawar was running about 50 km away
from Sukkur, a major city in Pakistan's southern Sindh province.
</P>
<P>
"Continuation of such acts of terrorism and making of innocent
civilians their victims would vitiate the atmosphere for a
constructive engagement for finding solutions to the problems in
the region," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The international community has stressed the necessity for a
dialogue to remove the root cause of the tensions in a nuclearized
South Asia," the statement said. "It is also clearly its
responsibility to denounce such acts of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
This was the second bomb blast in one week in Pakistan. On
Friday, a bomb blasted in a cinema in Lahore, capital of eastern
Punjab province, killing three and injuring one.
</P>
<P>
Last year, nearly 200 people were killed in various incidents
of terrorist and sectarian violence in Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
