<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Cracks Down on World Cup Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 7 (Xinhua) -- As the World Cup matches are
approaching, Thai police have launched a clamp-down on soccer
gambling operators who are set to earn an estimated 30 billion
baht (about 730 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This is part of a nationwide campaign against gambling that has
been on the rise in the recent years. Police feared that the World
Cup would add fuel to the gambling fever.
</P>
<P>
Police said gambling fever has spread everywhere -- from
private firms to government offices and from schools to local
banks.
</P>
<P>
With such huge stakes being bet, the notorious underground
lottery bookmakers have temporarily shifted their focus towards
soccer.
</P>
<P>
Police estimated that each gambler in Bangkok alone would spend
an average of 38,880 baht (about 948 dollars) to bet the upcoming
World Cup matches, 35 percent more than the sum during the 1994
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Central Investigation Bureau Deputy Commissioner
Maj. Gen. Chat Kuldilok acknowledged that lots of lottery
bookmakers had taken up soccer gambling because more money is
being spent on this sport.
</P>
<P>
Chat told reporters that Police Chief Gen. Pracha Promnok had
instructed the police to set up special squads to crack down on
the gambling-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
"We have asked police in each jurisdiction to come up with a
list of people who are involved in the gambling business," Chat
said.
</P>
<P>
But he said clamping-down on such an illegal business was a
daunting task.
</P>
<P>
The Police Department is seeking cooperation from banks, the
Education Ministry, University Affairs Ministry and the mass media
to help monitor the situation.
</P>
<P>
Chat said he had requested the banks to check on "suspicious"
transfers of large amounts of money among their customers.
</P>
<P>
"As for the media, we plead with them not to tacitly support
gambling. I know some of them even suggest betting prices," he
said, referring to newspaper columns which provide insights into
soccer matches.
</P>
<P>
Web sites available for gambling on the Internet also pose a
challenge to police. Education Ministry officials disclosed that
soccer gambling is very popular among students who have easy
access to web sites. Police have difficulty chasing and locating
such "Internet gamblers".
</P>
<P>
The Education Ministry has instructed teachers and rectors of
schools, colleges and universities to help prevent students from
using the Internet to bet on soccer games.
</P>
<P>
Schools in Bangkok have set up campus patrols in a bid to bar
students from sneaking out of their classrooms to wander around
shopping centers, computer game shops and theaters to bet on
soccer matches during the World Cup, a lecturer at Chulalongkhon
University in Bangkok said.
</P>
<P>
"Student patrols are not enough to deal with these students, so
we would like to ask shops to cooperate with us as well," said the
lecturer, who refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
A lottery bookmaker, who gave his name only as Wad, said in an
interview that since the number of his customers "is increasing
rapidly", he had to expand his network by setting up a special
pub. He said however that the pub is exclusively for "old" and
"loyal" customers.
</P>
<P>
He said most of his customers are middle-aged and normally opt
to bet 10,000 baht (244 U.S. dollars) on each match.
</P>
<P>
"We have already screened our customers, so there shouldn't be
any problem. We bet just for fun and most of our clients are
financially sound. We are not destroying the country, or the cash
flow in Thailand,' Wad said.
</P>
<P>
But a police officer, who preferred to be called Paitoon, said
gambling is eroding social morals and destabilizes the society.
</P>
<P>
"We must crack down on this illegal act for the sake of
Thailand," said Paitoon, who is a member of an anti-gambling
squad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Reorganize Civil Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government will
conduct a study on the possibility of mobilizing civil servants
from one department to another to cope with the manpower needs of
the public sector, according to the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The staff redeployment plan is to avoid new recruitment in line
with the government's objective to downsize the civil service,
Bernama quoted Chief Secretary to the Government Abdul Halim Ali
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysia Administrative Modernization and Manpower Planning
Unit in the Prime Minister's Department and the Public Services
Department would carry out the study on the optimum manpower
utilization in the civil service, the chief secretary said.
</P>
<P>
He said the study would also identify departments with excess
staff and reassign them to other departments without affecting
their work performance.
</P>
<P>
Manpower in certain areas could be reduced with the advent of
the electronic government, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said certain posts such as for teachers could not
be minimized due to the increasing population and the need to
provide education to the children.
</P>
<P>
He said candidates had been called for interviews to fill
certain vacancies but recruitment had been frozen due to the
economic downturn. "Filling of the vacancies will depend on the
country's economic situation," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
