<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Resume Destroyers-Building Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's navy may resume its
destroyer-building program later this year, said the Defense
Ministry Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to secure funds needed for the resumption of the
program named KDX-2, the Ministry draws up a revision to the
supplementary budget, which will be submitted to the National
Assembly in September for approval.
</P>
<P>
The KDX-2 destroyer, with a 30-knot speed and 4,000-mile range,
will be equipped with Harpoon ship-to-ship missiles, ship-to-air
missiles and anti-submarine rockets. It also has a launch pad for
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Under the KDX-2 program, nine 4,300-ton destroyers will be
built by Hyundai and Daewoo within seven to eight years, but the
number of warships to be built will be reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the navy was permitted to go ahead with a project of
1,500-ton submarines named SSU.
</P>
<P>
Both the KDX-2 and SSU programs, originally scheduled to start
early this year, were shelved as the Defense Ministry last December
cut their budget due to the nation's ongoing economic woes caused by
corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions late
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
