<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are business Briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt is going to promote the sale of state-owned
firms in the Arab world as well through outlets of Egyptian banks
in those countries, Public Enterprise Minister Atef Ebeid said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said only Egyptians would be allowed to subscribe to foreign
trade firms offered for sale, the Egyptian Gazette reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The would-be privatized companies include firms manufacturing
fertilizers, glassware and cement, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Sudan signed an agreement Saturday on
irrigation issues, including water conservation and weeds
elimination.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the end of the week-long meeting
of a joint Nile board in Cairo, which also called for greater
cooperation between the Nile countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- U.S. oil giant Amoco Corp. and an Egyptian company
have discovered a major oil deposit in the Gulf of Suez that is
being hailed as one of the country's richest finds.
</P>
<P>
The deposit was found at the end of May, an oil ministry
official said.
</P>
<P>
The deposit will "have proven production of 19,500 barrels a
day (bpd), one of the highest in Egypt," the official said, adding
that exploration was continuing in the area.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's total oil production in recent years has averaged
900,000 bpd but it has decided to cut output by 30,000 bpd from
July 1.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Investments in Jordan have increased by 53.9 percent
in the first half of this year over the same period of last year
to reach 131 million Jordanian dinars (about 185 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Investment Promotion Corporation
Muntasir Oqleh attributed the rise to the incentives by the
Investment Promotion Law which was endorsed at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Oqleh said that of the total sum of investments, 52.5 percent
came from non-Arab countries and 23.6 percent from Arab nations in
the region.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Pars Wagon Company (PWC) has signed an
agreement with Sudan to produce 500 various types of train wagons
for Khartoum, PWC managing director Ggholamreza Razazi announced
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He told the Iranian official news agency IRNA that the
contract of 25 million U.S. dollars was signed following the
visit to Tehran of a Sudanese delegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
