<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda Replaceable: UNIP Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the United National
Independence Party (UNIP) Malimba Masheke has said that UNIP has
capable leaders to take over the party presidency after its
leader Kenneth Kaunda retires from politics.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks two days after Kaunda announced his
intention to quit party politics at the next extraordinary
national congress.
</P>
<P>
He told Sunday Mail Saturday that Kaunda's retirement will not
create a vacuum in the party because it is capable of producing
another crop of leaders to take over the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
Masheke, who has been accused by some UNIP members of being
among a clique plotting to unseat Kaunda, said it is a myth to
say that UNIP will collapse after the departure of the former
president who ruled Zambia since its independence in 1964 until
1991 when he was defeated by current President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
"UNIP will find a new leader to take over from Dr. Kaunda just
like what other parties do and that the new leader will come from
within the party and not outside," Masheke said.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the charges made last week by UNIP Secretary
for Information and Publicity Bweendo Mulengela that he is no
longer in charge of the party because of an alleged misuse of
party funds, Masheke maintained that he is still party chairman.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is the only person who is legally empowered to
make statements concerning the party functions.
</P>
<P>
Masheke said that UNIP is consulting on the possibility of
holding a Central Committee meeting next week to be chaired by
Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda announced last Thursday he will quit party politics so
that he can serve the nation and the continent on a wider scope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Bans Tabloids for Publishing Pornography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government has
suspended the publication of three Kiswahili language tabloids
for persistent carrying pornographic cartoons and articles, state
media said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Prime Minister's Office Saturday
said the government was forced to make the decision after the
editors of the three newspapers had refused to heed to the
government warnings of not to continue with publications of
pornography.
</P>
<P>
The ban on Chombeza, Arusha Leo and Kasheshe, effective
Saturday, has been imposed in accordance with the Newspaper Act
of 1976 and the Newspaper Regulations of 1977, it said.
</P>
<P>
The press release went on to say that for several times the
editors and owners of the three tabloids have been summoned
before the Registrar of Newspapers for their bad performance. The
registrar has also written letters warning the papers' bad effect
on the general public, especially children.
</P>
<P>
It cited a cartoon on the front page of the Kasheshe,
depicting a suspected rape incident at a university in the city,
saying it sketched the bare genitals of a man, contrary to
newspaper ethics.
</P>
<P>
The Office of the Registrar of Newspapers has received many
complaints from the general public asking it to ban the three
newspapers because they were publishing articles and cartoons
detrimental to the Tanzanian culture.
</P>
<P>
"The government wants to insist the newspapers should respect
the social values in their society and therefore do away with
pornographic articles or cartoons or risk cancellation of their
registration, " the press release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
