<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Platinum Mine Losing $6M Per Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hartley Platinum Mine near
Harare is losing over six million U.S. Dollars every month due to
unforeseen mining complications, thereby threatening thousands of
workers now deployed with retrenchment or dismissal.
</P>
<P>
Manager for External Affairs of BHP Minerals Zimbabwe Simomo
Mubi confirmed Saturday that the mine, one of the largest
platinum mines in the world and jointly-owned by BHP and Delta
Gold, was currently operating at a negative cash flow lossing an
average of six million U.S. Dollars every month.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Mail quoted Mubi as saying that as a result of the
underground complications, the mine had failed to meet its
production target as the development rates of the main haulage
ways had been below target by over 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hartley Platinum project, which started about three years
ago, was hailed as the largest investment since independence in
1980.
</P>
<P>
Difficulties being experienced at the mine have been due to a
number of factors which include the loss of developed panels at a
section of mine known as the "South Portal" because of fractured
and weathered ground conditions, Mubi said.
</P>
<P>
"Numerous initiatives have been undertaken to overcome the
problems at Harley Mine," she said, adding that these included
increasing the development of haulage ways to seven days a week
and two blasts per day schedule.
</P>
<P>
Mubi said to enhance individual performance, the ongoing
training and development of miners, tradesmen and supervisors had
been accelerated.
</P>
<P>
The Hartley deposit was estimated to contain 50.9 million tons
of proven and probable reserves of platinum, rhodium, nickel,
palladium, gold and copper and it will produce 150,000 ounces of
platinum a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
