<HEADLINE> Educating Tourism Workers In Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
has set up an education system to train employees of the tourism
business.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry has 160,000 people there, only a third of
whom have any formal or professional education.
</P>
<P>
To provide more professional personnel, the province began
setting up three tourism schools, six training centers, and seven
tourism departments in colleges and universities in 1997. These
organizations can train 1,500 managers and 8,000 other personnel
in hotel work, accounting, foreign languages, designing tourism
products, or guide work.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province had 23.7 million domestic tourists and
800,000 foreign visitors, and did 1.19 billion yuan in tourist
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Diverse Exports For Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The municipality of Shanghai had
6.39 billion US dollars worth of exports for the January-May
period, up 8.9 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
A municipal government official says that exports to Asian
countries were down for the period, but those to the United
States, Europe, Latin America and Africa were up, which helped
ease pressures from the Asian financial crisis to some degree.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Shanghai has a goal of 16.3 billion US
dollars worth of exports for 1998, a 10.7-percent increase from
1997.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government is emphasizing market development to
encourage exports and has established a group working on trade
with Africa, to try to have one billion US dollars worth of
exports in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months, exports of electromechanical,
high-tech, and high value-added products increased, while
traditional exports like textiles and garments were down.
</P>
<P>
Exports of electromechanical products were worth 1.31 billion
US dollars in the January-April period, up 16 percent from the
same period of last year, while high-tech and high value-added
product exports were worth 820 million US dollars, up 51.8
percent. Textile and garment exports were down 8.2 percent and 6.8
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Exports of state-owned export companies and enterprises were
down at least 7 percent from the same period in 1997, while
foreign-funded enterprises exported 3.3 billion US dollars worth
of goods, up 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
