<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Pakistan Train Blast Rises to 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the train bomb
blast which took place Sunday morning in southern Pakistan rose to
23 and those injured were over 36, according to latest reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, reportedly planted in the middle of a carriage, went
off at about 4:10 a.m. (local time) Sunday when the train heading
for the northwestern city of Peshawar was running about 50 km away
from Sukkur, a major city in Pakistan's southern Sindh province.
</P>
<P>
Sindh Governor Moin Uddin Haider and other senior officials
from Sukkur authority have rushed to the scene of the incident to
supervise the relief and rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said they did not rule out the possibility of
terrorist motives behind the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports said that number of casualties may increase as
the authorities are searching the bodies along the track.
</P>
<P>
This was the second bomb blast in one week in Pakistan. On
Friday, a bomb blasted in a cinema in Lahore, capital of the
eastern Punjab province, killing three and injuring one.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 200 people were killed in the various terrorist and
sectarian violence in Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
