<HEADLINE> Havelange Hopes for Joint Korean Team for Next World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A united Korean team should be
fielded for the next World Cup and a mammoth stadium in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea's capital used for some of
the games, the outgoing president of soccer's world body said
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
FIFA president Joao Havelange said a joint North-South team had
been a success at the last under-16 world championships in
Portugal and that a similar effort for the World Cup would fulfill
one of the goals of his long-running presidency.
</P>
<P>
"My idea is to unite the two countries on the sports field for
the World Cup in 2002," Havelange said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said he had visited Pyongyang, DPRK's capital, four
times and seen the construction of a 100,000-seat stadium there.
</P>
<P>
"With a united team, perhaps that stadium could be used for
some matches," Havelange added.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and Japan were picked by FIFA to co-host the 2002
World Cup, the first time soccer's world championship will be held
in two nations.
</P>
<P>
Havelange, who steps down from the FIFA presidency after 24
years at the end of this year's World Cup, also said he hoped to
eventually help stage an exhibition match between Israel and
Palestine in New York. 
</P>
