<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rampant use of DDT Pollutes Bangladesh's Underground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The reckless use of DDT and
heptachlor are seriously contaminating the underground water in
Bangladesh's rural areas, creating health hazards for the people,
said a study reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Conducted by the National Minor Irrigation Development Project
in collaboration with the Bangladesh Atomic Energy Commission, the
study found the sub-soil water of different regions of the country
having traces of toxic residues of pesticides --DDT and
heptachlor, which are banned and allowed only for restricted use
in this South Asian country.
</P>
<P>
In most cases, heptachlor residues were found to be beyond the
World Health Organization recommended level of 0.03 microgram per
liter.
</P>
<P>
One of the samples contained heptachlor residue of 0.789
microgram per liter while DDT in another sample measured 1.527
microgram per liter, the study stated.
</P>
<P>
The presence of DDT and heptachlor residues indicates that the
contraband highly-toxic pesticides were still being used
indiscriminately in the country.
</P>
<P>
Percolation of carcinogenic pesticides including DDT and
heptachlor into human body might lead to cancer and neurological
problem, the study quoted M.A. Quayum, former chairman of the
Bangladesh Atomic Energy Commission, as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Olympic Speed Skater to Make a Comeback After Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Olympic medalist speed
skater Nikki Ziegelmeyer, who suffered a spinal injury while
training last year, said Saturday in New York that she will make a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
But the 22-year-old said she will compete in long-track speed
skating, instead of short-track.
</P>
<P>
"Short-track is too dangerous, " Ziegelmeyer said at a
hospital. "I made it through an injury once and I don't want to
press my luck."
</P>
<P>
She skated into a wall and fractured her vertebrae last October
while training for the Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan. Bone
fragments were crushed into her spinal canal, and it wasn't clear
whether she would ever walk again, said Allen Carl, her surgeon.
</P>
<P>
Her injury was the most serious suffered by a U.S. speed
skater. Ziegelmeyer won a bronze medal in the 1994 Winter Olympics
and a silver medal in the 1992 Olympics in short-track skating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
