<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200,000 Bangladeshis May Find Jobs Abroad This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- About 200,000 Bangladeshis may find
jobs abroad this year, with some 50 percent of them having
already gone to different countries with work, the Labor and
Manpower Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Those abroad have earned about 21.3 billion taka (46.3 million
U.S. dollars) in foreign currency for the country so far this
year, the Financial Express daily reported Sunday, quoting a
ministry source as saying recently.
</P>
<P>
As one of the country's major foreign exchange earners, labor
export earned 1.5 billion dollars during the past 1996-97 fiscal
year ending on June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
To create employment opportunities for Bangladeshi people
abroad, Labor and Manpower Minister M.A. Mannan, who is now in
Geneva, is trying to increase demand for Bangladeshi manpower
abroad, and the ministry has sent a letter to Bangladesh high
commissioner to South Africa to find out areas of employment in
Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The same letter has also been issued to labor attaches of
Bangladesh high commissions in ten other countries, including
Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Oman, Libya, and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
According to Labor and Manpower Secretary Ahsan Ali Sarker,
some countries such as Singapore were eager to import skilled
manpower. A training center has been set up in the country at the
request of a Singaporean company, he said.
</P>
<P>
With an area of about 144,000 square kilometers, Bangladesh has
a 127-million population, and a high jobless rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
