<HEADLINE> Share Prices on BSE Continue to Dip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Equities on India's premier
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market during the week received a
severe drubbing with the BSE sensitive index showing yet another
sharp fall.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index tumbled by another 268.50 points to end
the week at 3417.89 as against last weekend's close of 3686.39.
The national index also nose dived by 130.20 points to close the
week at 1513.94 from previous weekend close of 1644.14.
</P>
<P>
The budget for 1998-99 presented to Parliament on June 1 failed
to enthuse investors and the World Bank decided to put on hold all
loans to India. Stocks took a pounding as foreign funds and bulls,
disappointed by budgetary sops for industry, went on a selling
spree.
</P>
<P>
The gloom in the market worsened as the World Bank said last
week it was putting off talks on loans worth 800 million U.S.
dollars to India, and deferring indefinitely two other proposed
loans worth another 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market would have bad days ahead if the 3260
strong support level was broken in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
