<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Ethnic-Chinese Citizens Have Equal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
said here Saturday that the ethnic-Chinese community have equal
rights with other indigenous citizens.
</P>
<P>
"Both indigenous and non-indigenous Indonesians have the same
rights and obligations to the state and nation," Habibie told 50
editors of print and electronic media in a dialog forum.
</P>
<P>
A non-indigenous Indonesian who shows his commitment and takes
care of the national interests is much better and more respected
than an indigenous one, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic-Chinese has been targets for violence during times of
hardship in Indonesia in the past several decades. However, the
rioters have never been punished.
</P>
<P>
During the May 13-15 riots in Jakarta and elsewhere last month,
over 5,000 shops and homes of ethnic-Chinese were burned and
looted, and 1,193 people were killed, reports said.
</P>
<P>
There is still deep concern in the Chinese community over the
future, and a key to economic revival will be to attract back the
money from the community that moved out of the country some months
ago, said local English newspaper "The Sunday Observer".
</P>
<P>
According to a report published by the Forum of Reform
Entrepreneurs, about 110,000 families of Chinese descent had left
Indonesia since the riots erupted. Eighty thousand of the families
said they would return if the political and security situations
stabilized, 20,000 were still indecisive, and the remaining 10,000
had decided to move to Singapore and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
