<HEADLINE> China's Pharmaceutical Market Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China's increasing population of
seniors and growing demand in rural areas are indicating an
unprecedented opportunities to domestic drug manufacturers,
reports today's "Business Weekly."
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the State Pharmaceutical
Administration (SPA), China has more than 110 million senior
citizens above the age of 60. By year 2000, that figure is
expected to reach 130 million, accounting for 10.6 percent of the
nation's total population.
</P>
<P>
China's 864 million rural residents only accounts for 20
percent of the country's total pharmaceutical consumption. The
official says the increase of living standards in rural areas will
add to the market potential.
</P>
<P>
The pharmaceutical sector is profitable, accounting for 50
percent of all current and planned health care expenditures, and
constituting the largest single share of medical spending.
</P>
<P>
"China has become a major producer of medicines and
pharmaceutical instruments after two decades of continuous growth
averaging 17.5 percent, a rate much higher than in most developed
nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, total output value of the sector topped 120 billion
yuan (14.45 billion US dollars), tripling that of 1978.
</P>
<P>
Besides, China has formulated or revised many national and
professional standards for pharmaceutical products. So far, half
have reached the standards of developed countries, such as the
United States and Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
