<HEADLINE> Economic Briefs of South America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The following is major news
from the MERCOSUR -- the South American Common Market.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Direct foreign investment in Argentina amounted
to 6.327 billion dollars in 1997, a 24.3-percent increase over the
5.09 billion dollars of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Argentina received 2.7 billion U.S. dollars of foreign
investments each year from 1990 to 1993, and 3.8 billion dollars
each from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments went mainly to infrastructure and
communications projects.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil exported 178,115 motor vehicles in the first
five months of this year, an increase of 23.78 percent over the
year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
Brazil motor vehicles found new markets in the United States,
Russia, Australia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is expected to produce two million motor vehicles this
year.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil will be the first country in the world to
produce a variety of trans-genetic soybean resistant to herbicides
of the imidazolinones group.
</P>
<P>
The new soybean will allow farmers to use new herbicides, as
well as those already existing in the market.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the second largest soybean producer in the world with
an annual output of 30 million tons.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Eduardo Amadeo, secretary of Programming for
the Prevention of Drug Addiction and War on Drug Traffic,
presented Congress June 2 a bill against money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The bill aims to punish crimes including money laundering and
any crime related to terrorism and the production, transportation
and marketing of drugs.
</P>
<P>
It also covers the illegal trade of organs and human beings,
extortion, kidnapping and frauds. 
</P>
