<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CAAC Restricts Air-fare Discounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Heavy losses of domestic airlines
have prompted the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) to
impose restrictions on air-fare discounts on domestic routes and
stop irrational price war of air transport, reported today's
"Business Weekly."
</P>
<P>
The capacity of Air China's Shanghai-Beijing route jumped to
more than 80 percent soon after CAAC set out a 20-percent ceiling
on domestic discounts in late April.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, 11 large domestic airlines
suffered losses totalling 1.7 billion yuan (204 million US
dollars), according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The "Business Weekly" quoted Air China Vice-President Fu Baoxin
as saying that one of the reasons for the decline is that the
number of available seats "has been slightly higher than demand"
in the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
CAAC wants domestic carriers to forge alliances to lower costs
and improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, this consolidation has been derailed due to
protectionism exercised by local governments," said an official
with a large airline.
</P>
<P>
These local civil aviation companies have gained the upper hand
in the price war because of limited air routes, low operating
costs, flexible management and fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
Participation of foreign airlines on international routes from
and to China has also put a crimp in the earnings of China's big
three airlines: China Southern Airlines, China Eastern Airlines
and Air China.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the 7.6 million international air
passengers arriving and leaving China used foreign airlines in
1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the domestic aviation industry still has immense
potential, the "Business Weekly" says.
</P>
<P>
Only one out of every 24 people in China travel by air each
year, in sharp contrast to the United States, where on average
each person takes at least two flights a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's SEZs Protect Environment Well While Economy Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- China's eastern coastal city of
Xiamen, in a time of rapid economic growth, has still managed to
maintain a fine environment, with the quality of air and sea water
up to first grade of the national criteria.
</P>
<P>
One of China's five Special Economic Zones (SEZs), the
131-sq-km island city has witnessed a growth of industrial output
of nearly 40 times in the past two decades without sacrificing the
environment. It has been cited as a national model of
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the State Bureau of Environmental Protection show
that China's first group of six environmental protection models
include three SEZs -- Xiamen, Shenzhen and Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
Instead of following the old framework of "pollution first and
treatment afterwards" adopted by many countries during their
economic development, China's SEZs have achieved sturdy economic
growth at the minimum environmental cost.
</P>
<P>
Wu Zilin, director of Xiamen's environmental protection
bureau, said the city has always attached great importance to
environmental protection, and no project producing serious
pollution is allowed to be set up there.
</P>
<P>
When Xiamen obtained autonomous legislative power in 1994 the
first local law passed was one on environmental protection, Wu
said.
</P>
<P>
China's largest SEZ, the island province of Hainan, has drawn
up more than 20 laws and regulations on environmental protection
over the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
As all the leading officials of China's SEZs consider a fine
environment to be an important factor in attracting foreign
investment, each SEZ is doing its utmost to protect its
environment.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen injected 2.08 percent of its GDP into environmental
protection last year, compared to 1.85 percent in 1996. The
environmental protection investment is expected to reach three
percent of the city's GDP this year.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen directly poured 773 million yuan (about 93.3 million
US dollars) into environmental protection in the first half of
last year, while Shantou earmarks five million yuan for
environmental protection every year.
</P>
<P>
Wu Zilin said Xiamen's environmental protection efforts have
been rewarded at least in two aspects -- a clean and beautiful
environment its citizens and a steady inflow of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of April Xiamen had actually
used foreign funds worth 8.12 billion yuan and introduced 4,366
foreign-funded projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
