<HEADLINE> 11 Killed in Philippine Army, Rebels Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Eleven people, including five
soldiers, were killed in separate gunbattles Friday between the
Philippine army and Muslim rebels in the southern Philippines, the
newspaper Manila Standard reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Citing military reports, the newspaper said that a patrol team
of the Army's 26th Infantry Battalion was ambushed by a band of
the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in Sapad town,
Lanao del Norte province in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Three soldiers were killed and six others wounded in the
ambush, while three guerrillas were reported killed on the MILF
side.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group was led by Kadi Abdullah who reportedly
withdrew into the hinterlands with remnants of his group before
the arrival of reinforcing government troops.
</P>
<P>
In Zamboanga City, capital of Zamboanga province, another
contingent of armymen clashed with another MILF rebel group
Friday, resulting in the death of two troopers, two rebels and a
pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which has fought for a separate Islamic state in
Mindanao for decades, is currently the strongest anti-government
troops in the Philippines, with an estimated membership of more
than 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The MILF began low-level peace talks with the government in
January 1997, but the two sides have so far failed to reach an
agreement on the timetable for formal peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
