<DOCNO> XIE19980607.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Needs Participation of Private Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior trade expert recently
suggested that the government allows private companies to
participate more in China's foreign trade, as the Asian financial
crisis has made it more urgent to do so.
</P>
<P>
Qin Xuanren, deputy-secretary general of China Association of
International Trade, told Business Weekly that "the participation
of private foreign trade firms will definitely reinforce China's
foreign trade."
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed the worry that the establishment of private
foreign trade firms will hurt state-owned ones.
</P>
<P>
Qin said a minimum 1.4 percent growth rate for exports must be
reached to ensure this year's national economy of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's state-owned foreign trade firms, which used to be the
backbone of China's exports, are falling short of capacity, and
many of them are suffering from heavy debts, reported today's
"Business Weekly."
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial turmoil, which has caused sluggish import
demand and increased the export competitiveness of the affected
countries, has worsened China's foreign trade situation, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, more aggressive foreign-invested companies and
manufacturing enterprises with foreign trade rights have quickly
emerged as the mainstay of China's export industry.
</P>
<P>
Private foreign trade firms will only act as a complement to
their state-owned counterparts, and they can also force
state-owned firms to reform their operation, the "Business Weekly"
quoted Qin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Private firms will be mainly engaged in the import and export
of goods like shoes, clothes and toys, while state-owned ones will
control the bulk of large electronics and machinery products, such
as planes and ships, he suggested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
