<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Purifies Scenic Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The water quality of Dianchi Lake,
a major scenic spot just outside this capital of southwest China's
Yunnan Province and the sixth-largest freshwater lake in China, is
expected to be considerably improved by the year 2000, according
to a city official.
</P>
<P>
A major source of water for Kunming, the lake has been polluted
by increasing amounts of industrial and domestic sewage water in
recent years. Official figures show that 50,000 tons of waste
water flows into the lake each day.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the '99 World Garden Exposition, to be held
here from May to October next year, Yunnan has earmarked a large
amount of money to clean up Dianchi Lake, an effort that is
supported by the central authorities and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The purification project, estimated to cost 2.6 billion yuan
including 150 million US dollars in World Bank loans, includes
building and renovating five sewage-disposal plants and the
construction of an lake-environment monitoring system.
</P>
<P>
After the completion of the project in May 1999, Kunming's
sewage water disposal rate will exceed 80 percent and the amount
of pollutants deposited in the lake will be reduced by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Besides the main project, several subsidiary projects involving
the installation of pipelines and the building of pumping stations
have also been started to help improve the overall environment and
ecology in the lake area.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
