<HEADLINE> Record Cold Strikes Central U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Temperatures dropped to record
lows across the central part of the United States on Saturday,
hitting some areas with frozen degrees.
</P>
<P>
The cold air from Canada was spread across the Plains, Great
Lakes, Ohio Valley and Mississippi Valley. Low-temperature records
toppled or were tied in 50 cities in Michigan, Ohio, Indiana,
Kentucky, Missouri, Arkansas, Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska,
Colorado and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
Along the eastern slopes of the Rockies, the temperature
dropped to a record minus 2.2 degree centigrade at Alamosa,
Colorado, to minus 1.6 degree centigrade in parts of Wyoming and
to 1.1 degrees at Denver, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
In Detroit, Michigan, and Dayton, Ohio, it tied a 5 degrees
centigrade record that has been on the books since 1894. The 0.9
degree low temperature at Scottsbluff, Nebraska, broke a record
set in 1899.
</P>
<P>
In Texas, the Panhandle city of Amarillo posted a record of 5
degrees and Abilene had a record 11.5 degrees. South Texas just
suffered a heat wave a few days ago with a temperature of as
high as 42 degrees centigrade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
