<HEADLINE> Russia Beats Australia to Play for Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia, who disqualified for last
championship four years ago, survived a strong comeback and
revenged Australia 82-76 Saturday, advancing to the final at the
Women's World Basketball Championship.
</P>
<P>
This was a repeat game of the Atlanta Olympic semi-final in
1996 when Australia edge Russia by four points, 74-70.
</P>
<P>
"This is our best game at this World Championship" said Elena
Baranova, who led the Russians with 25 points, 14 rebounds and 4
assists. "We have improved game by game and are playing our best
World Championship for a long time. We defeated the Australians
by our strong defense."
</P>
<P>
The WNB star was surported by Elena Pshikova's 22 points
including five 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
Russia will meet with another semi-final winner between the
United States and Brazil in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
"We are capable of producing the unforced errors, we will have
a good chance in tomorrow's final," said Evgueny Gomelksy, the
famous Russian head coach.
</P>
<P>
"Australia has a very good team. They put us under pressure for
a long time by their pressing defense. I think Australia will be
even stronger in two years and has a good chance to win the gold
medal at the Olympics."
</P>
<P>
Russia started with a 19-11 lead only six minutes 29 seconds
into the game, but was surpassed 24-23 on Lauren Jackson's
straight six points with 7:34 to play in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Then game leveled four times and changed several time in scores
with a 36-36 halftime equal.
</P>
<P>
It seemed Russia could win without the problem after forward
Elena Pshikova hit her fifth 3-pointers to promote the Russians'
advantage to 60-44 with 10:39 left.
</P>
<P>
Australia, fourth place finisher four years ago at home and
Olympic bronze midalist, fired two spurts in the span of less than
eight minutes to narrowed the margin by only two points for 74-76.
</P>
<P>
But the well-coached Russian team finally prevented from their
opponents' last rally to seal the berth of the gold medal final.
</P>
<P>
Forward Michelle Griffiths was the top scorer for Australia
with 17 points while Michele Timms scored 14.
</P>
<P>
"Russian scored in 50 percent of their shots, we only in 30
percent. In addition, the Russians dominated the rebounds,"
Australian coach Tom Maher said.
</P>
<P>
"They have good players, a well-balanced team. Contrary to my
team, they shot very well and successfully," the Austrlian coach
added.
</P>
<P>
The United States meets defending champion Brazil later Friday
night. 
</P>
