<HEADLINE> Hackers Hit U.S. Army Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Hackers entered U.S. Army
computers last week and altered a command's Web site, The U.S.
Army said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Army spokesman Gerry Gilmore was quoted by the Associated Press
as saying, "Evidently they went through some Army organization's
computers."
</P>
<P>
Gilmore said the hackers apparently got into the Army's
computers Thursday through its Dental Command system at Fort Sam
Houston, Texas.
</P>
<P>
Gilmore said the home page, the title page, was altered. But He
would not elaborate on the type of information the hackers gained
or if U.S. security was compromised.
</P>
<P>
Gilmore also did not comment about whether the hackers used the
Army access to enter the Indian government computers.
</P>
<P>
Days earlier, computer hackers claimed to have entered India's
national security computer network and stolen sensitive nuclear
weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
They also said in an interview with the online magazine Wired
News that they altered a World Wide Web site there.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Jim Turner said that "the appropriate
authorities are looking into it." The FBI and the Army were
investigating the matter.
</P>
<P>
The six hackers, who call themselves the MilwOrm Group, said
they are 15-18 years old and hail from the United States, England,
the Netherlands and New Zealand. They claim to have accessed
electronic mail messages sent between India's nuclear scientists
and Israeli government officials as well as downloaded sensitive
documents, the Associated Press report said.
</P>
<P>
They also altered the Web site of the Bhabha Atomic Research
Center, the nerve center of India's nuclear programs, they said in
the online interview. 
</P>
</TEXT>
